text: This is awful news for the families and our sympathies are with them. These are testing times. We are so grateful for the courage and dedication of our firefighters.

Devastated at the terrible news of the loss of another volunteer firefighter and two others injured near Jingellic in southern NSW where a truck has rolled over. In a separate vehicle another firefighter has been injured.

Today marks a week since the tragedy on Whakaari/White Island in NZ, which so far has claimed 19 lives, including 10 Australians, and left many others with horrific injuries.

This photo was taken at our IMB Cook Community Classic at North Cronulla beach yesterday, where I took part in my first 1km ocean swim. I set the Classic up with our local surf clubs about 12 years ago to bring our community together & raise money for local clubs and charities.

A heartfelt thank you to all those volunteers and surf lifesavers for your service. And for those Australians heading to the beach this summer, swim between the flags, follow the instructions of those wearing those red and yellow caps, & stay safe.

30 people are rescued by our surf lifesaving movement in Australia, every day. We are not aware of any Australians being caught up in these attacks at this stage, but we are in close contact with local authorities.

Just terrible news out of London & The Hague. Whether it has been the despicable acts of terrorists in the UK, or as yet not determined in the Netherlands, Australians’ deepest sympathies are with the victims & their families - they were innocent people going about their lives.

Australians are saddened by the passing of Clive James. He was a great novelist, poet, wit and personality who showcased the good humour and good nature of Australians. Clive had a deep love for our country, and expressed that deep affection in all that he said and did.

Continuing to expand opportunities for our exporters is key to our plan to strengthen our economy. As PM, it’s at times like these I’m never more proud of Australians. The incredible spirit, heart, & generosity on display today, whether it was at the evacuation centre or the courage & professionalism of the fire fighters battling these blazes, really was something to behold.

This is Owen. I met him at the Taree Evacuation Centre. He, like many other people, is facing an anxious time, but was pleased his dogs had survived the fire. My heart goes out to him & the people I met today, who shared their stories of heartbreak but also resilience.

The fires burning in NSW & Queensland are simply terrifying. To those Australians who have lost everything, we are devastated at your loss & we’ll be there to support & rebuild. To all those in affected areas stay safe & please listen to & follow emergency services instructions.

This Monday is #RemembranceDay when we pause to remember those who made the ultimate sacrifice for Australia. There is much to do both immediately & for the longer term. There are no easy solutions & we will apply ourselves totally. This is all about the people we love & cherish. All older Australians should get the same care, support & dignity we would expect for our own families.

Last year I initiated the Royal Commission into Aged Care. It was one of my first acts as PM. Today we have been handed the Interim Report. As warned, it’s shocking, disturbing & heartbreaking. We must establish a new culture of respect for senior Australians.

Congratulations to PM @JustinTrudeau on his election victory in Canada. Looking forward to continuing our strong working relationship and the partnership between Australia and Canada.

Congrats to the 26,200 Australians who secured a full-time job in Sept, helping the unemployment rate fall to 5.2%. Our Government’s job record is strong, with 3 years of consecutive monthly jobs growth, the longest run in our history & 1.47m jobs created since we came to office.

Today we announced more help for farmers doing it tough in this unrelenting drought. We’ll give those who’ve come to the end of their 4 years financial assistance a one-off payment of up to $13k. That’s on top of the around $100k they’ve received. It doesn’t have to be paid back.

Labor had 6 yrs in Govt to remove GST on sanitary items & did nothing. They promised to do it before the last election & reversed that promise before the election was held. Labor always wants you to judge them on what they say & promise, not what they do. We just get on with it.

Over the next 4 yrs states and territories will receive an additional $6.5b in GST revenue because of changes we have made to improve the integrity of the tax system. Agreeing to remove GST from sanitary items is a modest change and totally doable from a financial perspective.

It is a practical issue. There’s no great gender conspiracy. It’s just a tax anomaly that can be fixed if all the states agree. Sure, there are much bigger issues - the drought, electricity prices, jobs - just to name a few. But that doesn’t mean we can’t deal with this as well.

Three years ago Joe Hockey asked State and Territory Treasurers to remove the GST from sanitary products. They didn’t agree. We have decided to give this another go so in June I wrote to them to ask them again. This time, I hope they agree.
